So Halma is interesting:

 

*	They have 6000 employees spread across around 40 companies
*	They acquire small to medium companies in the "health technology"
sector but then leave them to be run autonomously (presumably by existing
management)
*	They don't seem to sell those companies like a fund would, think
they just raise funds on the stock market and invest them to form a
conglomerate
*	Halma has a "purpose" and an "organisation culture" but the
specifics are presumably set at the individual company level
*	I checked a few of the companies and most have a "mission" and
"vision" but no "values" - so I wonder how Halma thinks about the cultural
link across companies
*	So lots of ways to pitch it - what do they know about the culture in
each of their companies? How do they know if the culture in a company
matches their overall purpose? What tools do they give their companies to
help them manage their culture?

 

C


